1. Handling Request Bodies with @RequestBody

Theory:
@RequestBody tells Spring to convert incoming JSON (or XML) into a Java object.
Used for POST and PUT requests, where the client sends data.

Implementation:

@PostMapping("/users")
public User createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
    // 'user' is automatically populated from the JSON request body
    return userService.save(user);
}

How it works:
The client sends JSON like { "name": "Alice", "email": "alice@example.com" }.
Spring uses Jackson to convert this JSON into a User object.


2. Returning JSON or XML Responses with Jackson

Theory:
By default, Spring uses Jackson to convert Java objects to JSON for responses.
If you want XML, you can add the Jackson XML dependency.

Implementation:

@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
public User getUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
    // Returns a User object as JSON (or XML if configured)
    return userService.findById(id);
}

How it works:
Spring automatically serializes the returned object to JSON (or XML).
The client receives a response like { "id": 1, "name": "Alice" }.

To support XML:

Add this dependency to your Maven/Gradle:

<dependency>
    <groupId>com.fasterxml.jackson.dataformat</groupId>
    <artifactId>jackson-dataformat-xml</artifactId>
</dependency>

3. Using ResponseEntity for Fine Control Over HTTP Responses and Status Codes

Theory:

ResponseEntity lets you control the HTTP status code, headers, and body of the response.
Useful for sending custom status codes (like 404, 201), headers, or error messages.

Implementation:

@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<User> getUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
    User user = userService.findById(id);
    if (user == null) {
        return ResponseEntity.notFound().build(); // 404 Not Found
    }
    return ResponseEntity.ok(user); // 200 OK with user data
}

@PostMapping("/users")
public ResponseEntity<User> createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
    User createdUser = userService.save(user);
    return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.CREATED).body(createdUser); // 201 Created
}

How it works:

You can set the status code (200, 201, 404, etc.).
You can set the response body (user data, error message).
You can add custom headers.

4. Adding Custom HTTP Headers

Theory:

Sometimes you need to send extra information in headers (like authentication tokens,
custom metadata).

Implementation:

@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<User> getUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
    User user = userService.findById(id);
    if (user == null) {
        return ResponseEntity.notFound().build();
    }
    HttpHeaders headers = new HttpHeaders();
    headers.add("X-Custom-Header", "CustomValue");
    return ResponseEntity.ok().headers(headers).body(user);
}

How it works:

(i) You create a HttpHeaders object.
(ii) Add custom headers.
(iii) Attach headers to the ResponseEntity.


